er 1388–25 October 1415","1390–1414":"1390–1414","1413–1460":"1413–1460","1388–1415":"1388–1415","1415":"1415","1414":"1414","1413":"1413","Aft 1414":"after 1414","1388":"1388","13 Dec 1388":"13 December 1388","1460":"1460","1409":"1409","25 Oct 1415":"25 October 1415","1390":"1390","Battle of Agincourt, Meurthe & Moselle, France":"Agincourt, Meurthe-et-Moselle, Grand Est, France","England":"England, United Kingdom","Stratfield Mortimer, Berkshire, England":"Stratfield Mortimer, Berkshire, England","Tedstone Wafer Bromyard. Herefordshire":"Bromyard, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Mortimer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Mortemer in Seine-Maritime, France, so called from Old French <i>mort(e)</i> ‘dead’ + <i>mer</i> ‘sea’, probably referring to a stagnant pond or drained swamp.","Irish (of Norman origin): the Norman surname in sense 1 above was taken to Ireland from England in the medieval period, where it has also been adopted by bearers of the Gaelic surnames <b>Mac Muircheartaigh</b> and <b>ÓMuircheartaigh</b>, commonly Anglicized as <b>McMurty</b> and <b>Mortagh</b>. Compare   McMurdo  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mortimore","meanings":["English (Devon; of Norman origin): variant of   Mortimer  ."]},{"name":"McMurdo","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Muircheartaigh</b> or <b>Mac Muircheartaich</b>, ‘son of Muircheartach’, a personal name meaning ‘sea-ruler’. In Scotland the name was often lenited to give   McCurdy  . Compare   Murdoch   and   Moriarty  . The name was also used to Anglicize <i>Mac Murchaidh</i> (see   McMorrow  )."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Roger De Mortimer was born on 13 December 1388, in Bromyard, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom. He married Elizabeth in 1409, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 25 October 1415, in Agincourt, Meurthe-et-Moselle, Grand Est, France, at the age of 26."},"et":{"13 Dec 1388–25 Oct 1415":"13. detsember 1388–25. oktoober 1415","1390–1414":"1390–1414","1413–1460":"1413–1460","1388–1415":"1388–1415","1415":"1415","1414":"1414","1413":"1413","Aft 1414":"pärast 1414","1388":"1388","13 Dec 1388":"13. detsember 1388","1460":"1460","14